<font color="#FF0000">HELP!!!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 19  4:44:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
     I am in a relationship with a Vietnam Veteran with diagnosed PTSD.  He has done everything to scare me away with his irrational, explosive anger (no physical violence), hypersensitivity, and paranoia, but I have seen the beautiful soul that exists under all of the pain and I just can't give in to his sense of hopelessness - he believes that he is &quot;damaged goods&quot; sentenced to a tragic existence alone, believing he will only bring me pain, in spite of our incredible connection,love and commitment to one another.  The shame he feels after these outbursts hurts his pride even deeper and he then feels torn between his habit of isolating and his urge to be close to me.  Reading the experiences of the men on this page has helped me to understand that what I am experiencing with him is not unusual for what he has been through, but I am at a loss as to what I can do to help him through some of this pain.  I am a wise woman who realizes that he will probably never be free of the scars of this horrific experience, but I only hope that we can reach a point where my lovingness towards him doesn't trigger all of his distrust and fear of intimacy (he has had many years of therapy, has come a long way, but believes this is as far as he can go).  I was hoping that some of you who can relate to his hell can help me understand (through your past experiences with wifes or girlfriends) what to do to support him.  He says that I am everything that he has ever dreamed of and now feels like this is some kind of cruel joke, because he feels incapable of maintaining it.  The juggling act is overwhelming at times - when he goes into his wild accusations, I feel the inate need to defend myself (calmly) which only seems to escalate things...how do I maintain my dignity while still moving toward peace and growth?  Everyone in his life has turned his back on him - I will not - I will do anything short of sacrificing my self esteem to save this relationship, but I am at a loss as how to proceed.  I have never been a martyr nor a masochist...I simply met a wonderful man with a beautiful heart carrying the pain of the Universe and I need help understanding how I can help wake him up from his nightmare.   The wisdom of your experiences would be greatly appreciated.    
<p><code>--   (Beth) </code><p>


